&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From:	Dinwiddie, George [SMTP:George.Dinwiddie@...]
&gt; Sent:	Thursday, March 15, 2001 12:57 PM
&gt; To:	&#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39;
&gt; Subject:	RE: [junit] awkward mock objects
&gt; 
&gt; Neil,
&gt; 
&gt; Eh?  I&#39;m not sure I understand your intent.
&gt; 
&gt; I just wanted to create a mock object that would return canned data.
&gt; But I had to implement ALL of the methods defined by the interface
&gt; in order to compile.  The &quot;interesting&quot; method is what I wanted to
&gt; override; it&#39;s all the uninteresting methods I had to type that were
&gt; a pain.  So, I implemented a abstract base class named
&gt; AbstractMockResultSet.
&gt; Then, whenever I need a mock ResultSet, I can override only the method
&gt; (or handful of methods) that are interesting to me for the test.
&gt; 
&gt;  - George
&gt; 
&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From: Neil Swingler [mailto:nswingler@...]
&gt; Sent: Thursday, March 15, 2001 12:45 PM
&gt; To: junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt; Subject: RE: [junit] awkward mock objects
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; With JDK1.3, you could use java.lang.reflect.Proxy to delegate to a class
&gt; containing only the interesting methods
&gt; 
&gt; -- Neil Swingler
&gt; 
&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From: Dinwiddie, George [mailto:George.Dinwiddie@...]
&gt; Sent: 15 March 2001 17:34
&gt; To: &#39;junit@yahoogroups.com&#39;
&gt; Subject: [junit] awkward mock objects
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; Speaking of mock objects, I needed to test some objects that initialized
&gt; themselves from a JDBC ResultSet.  Rather than generate a test table and
&gt; stuff data into it, I decided to create a MockResultSet.  Well, ResultSet
&gt; is
&gt; an interface with a LOT of methods.  What a boring chore this turned out
&gt; to
&gt; be.  In the end, I created an AbstractMockResultSet class that throws an
&gt; SQLException for every method.  If anyone needs such a thing, let me know
&gt; and it could save you a lot of typing.
&gt; 
